{
  "texts": [
    "Larger models typically produce more fluent and accurate annotations but are not universally superior-especially when prompts are poorly designed or tasks are highly contextual.",
    "Second, prompt complexity and robustness plays a key role.",
    "Mu et al. [10] find that simpler prompts tend to yield more reliable results than multi-step or overly verbose instructions.",
    "Huang et al. [11] and Lu et al.",
    "[12] further show that complex reasoning chains or \"effective\" prompts often fail when transferred across tasks or re-ordered, exposing their fragility."
  ]
}